Consumer Group Management
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of Apache Kafka architecture (topics, partitions, producers)
Familiarity with Linux command line
Completed previous Kafka labs or equivalent experience
Java 11+ installed on your system
Learning Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Configure and manage Kafka consumer groups
Understand consumer group coordination and partition assignment
Test and observe consumer rebalancing behavior
Monitor consumer group lag and offsets
Environment Setup
Install Apache Kafka
# Download Kafka
cd ~
wget https://archive.apache.org/dist/kafka/3.6.0/kafka_2.13-3.6.0.tgz
tar -xzf kafka_2.13-3.6.0.tgz
cd kafka_2.13-3.6.0

# Set environment variable for convenience
export KAFKA_HOME=~/kafka_2.13-3.6.0
export PATH=$PATH:$KAFKA_HOME/bin
Start Kafka Services
# Start ZooKeeper
$KAFKA_HOME/bin/zookeeper-server-start.sh -daemon $KAFKA_HOME/config/zookeeper.properties

# Wait 5 seconds
sleep 5

# Start Kafka broker
$KAFKA_HOME/bin/kafka-server-start.sh -daemon $KAFKA_HOME/config/server.properties

# Wait 10 seconds for broker to start
sleep 10
Create Test Topic
# Create topic with 4 partitions for testing rebalancing
$KAFKA_HOME/bin/kafka-topics.sh --create \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --topic orders \
  --partitions 4 \
  --replication-factor 1

# Verify topic creation
$KAFKA_HOME/bin/kafka-topics.sh --describe \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --topic orders
Task 1: Configure Consumer Groups
Step 1: Create Consumer Configuration Files
Create a directory for consumer configurations:

mkdir -p ~/kafka-lab/consumers
cd ~/kafka-lab/consumers
Create the first consumer configuration file:

cat > consumer1.properties << 'EOF'
bootstrap.servers=localhost:9092
group.id=order-processing-group
key.deserializer=org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer
value.deserializer=org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer
auto.offset.reset=earliest
enable.auto.commit=true
auto.commit.interval.ms=1000
session.timeout.ms=10000
heartbeat.interval.ms=3000
EOF
Create a second consumer configuration with different settings:

cat > consumer2.properties << 'EOF'
